.in%2Fhistory%2Findians-a-history-web-series-namit-arora%5C%22%3EA%20Brief%20History%20of%20a%20Civilisation%20and%20Why%20We%20Need%20to%20Know%20it%3C%2Fa%3E%20%7C%202.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fhistory%2Findians-the-aryans-and-the-vedic-age%5C%22%3EThe%20Aryans%20and%20the%20Vedic%20Age%3C%2Fa%3E%20%7C%203.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fhistory%2Fwatch-indians-episode-3-the-mauryans-and-megasthenes%5C%22%3EThe%20Mauryans%20and%20Megasthenes%3C%2Fa%3E%20%7C%204.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fhistory%2Fwatch-indians-episode-4-the-ikshvakus-of-andhra-pradesh%5C%22%3EThe%20Ikshvakus%20of%20Andhra%20Pradesh%3C%2Fa%3E.%20%7C%205.%20%3C%2Fem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fhistory%2Fwatch-indians-episode-5-nalanda-and-the-decline-of-buddhism%5C%22%3ENalanda%20and%20the%20Decline%20of%20Buddhism%3C%2Fa%3E%20%7C%206.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fhistory%2Fwatch-indians-episode-6-khajuraho-and-the-world-of-tantra%5C%22%3EKhajuraho%20and%20the%20World%20of%20Tantra%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3E%3Cspan%3EIn%20the%20early%20second%20millennium%2C%20two%20famous%20travellers%20visited%20India%3A%20Alberuni%20and%20Marco%20Polo%2C%20who%E2%80%99ve%20left%20behind%20vivid%20impressions%20of%20social%20life.%20Alberuni%2C%20a%20great%20scientist%20and%20scholar%20of%20the%20Persian%20%E2%80%98Golden%20Age%E2%80%99%2C%20was%20in%20north%20India%20between%201017%E2%80%9330%2C%20when%20Mahmud%20of%20Ghazni%20was%20raiding%20temples.%20Led%20by%20his%20own%20curiosity%2C%20Alberuni%20spent%2013%20years%20studying%20Indian%20thought%20and%20society.%20He%20learned%20Sanskrit%2C%20studied%20the%20works%20of%20Brahminism%2C%20and%20sought%20out%20learned%20men%20to%20clarify%20his%20doubts.%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3E%3Cspan%3EIn%201030%2C%20he%20published%20his%20magnum%20opus%2C%20Alberuni%E2%80%99s%20India%2C%20containing%20sharp%20insights%20into%20Brahminical%20religion%2C%20scriptures%2C%20caste%2C%20marital%20norms%2C%20festivals%2C%20inheritance%2C%20taxes%2C%20crime%20and%20punishment%2C%20etc.%20He%20also%20assessed%20the%20quality%20of%20the%20%E2%80%98Hindu%20sciences%E2%80%99.%20Alberuni%E2%80%99s%20portrait%20of%20India%20is%20so%20perceptive%20that%20he%20deserves%20to%20be%20called%20the%20%E2%80%98first%20Indologist%E2%80%99.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3E%3Cspan%3EMarco%20Polo%20was%20a%20Venetian%20merchant%20%E2%80%93%20adventurer.%20Returning%20home%20from%20China%20in%201292%2C%20he%20stopped%20in%20south%20India.%20He%20landed%20in%20the%20kingdom%20of%20the%20Pandyas%2C%20near%20modern%20Thanjavur%20in%20Tamil%20Nadu.%20He%20spent%20a%20few%20months%20going%20around%20the%20coast%2C%20finally%20sailing%20out%20of%20Gujarat.%20Marco%20Polo%20was%20less%20scholarly%20and%20more%20gullible%20than%20Alberuni%2C%20but%20he%20still%20astutely%20recorded%20many%20practices%20of%20religion%20and%20caste%2C%20customs%20and%20professions%2C%20norms%20of%20beauty%20and%20sexuality.%20These%20travellers%20add%20colour%20and%20depth%20to%20our%20understanding%20of%20medieval%20India%2C%20with%20rich%20insights%20into%20how%20much%20has%20%E2%80%93%20or%20hasn%E2%80%99t%202%20%E2%80%93%20changed.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cdiv%3E%3Ciframe%20allowfullscreen%3D%5C%22allowfullscreen%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fembed%2FqVsgT18hr34%3Fsi%3DHlbgH49tqjXXUsYj%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22560%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22YouTube%20video%20player%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22315%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EThe%20full%20transcript%20of%20the%20video%20is%20below.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EHello%20and%20welcome%20to%20Indians.%20I%E2%80%99m%20Namit%20Arora.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EIn%20the%20previous%20episode%2C%20we%20looked%20at%20the%20Chandela%20kingdom%20at%20Khajuraho%2C%20and%20how%20its%20erotic%20temple%20art%20was%20shaped%20by%20tantric%20religiosity.%20We%20examined%20the%20hedonistic%20culture%20of%20its%20elites%2C%20and%20why%20it%20started%20declining%2C%20long%20before%20the%20Turko-Persian%20invasions%20of%20north%20India.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3ELet%E2%80%99s%20now%20look%20at%20two%20famous%20travellers%20who%20visited%20India%2C%20and%20their%20impressions%20of%20social%20life%20in%20the%20early%202nd%20millennium.%20The%20first%20is%20Alberuni%2C%20who%20frequented%20north%20India%20between%201017%20and%201030%2C%20when%20Mahmud%20of%20Ghazni%20was%20raiding%20temples%20in%20India.%20The%20second%20is%20Marco%20Polo%2C%20who%20visited%20south%20India%20in%201292%2C%20just%20a%20few%20decades%20before%20the%20rise%20of%20the%20Vijayanagar%20Empire.%20Their%20accounts%20add%20colour%20and%20depth%20to%20our%20understanding%20of%20medieval%20India%2C%20with%20rich%20insights%20into%20how%20much%20has%E2%80%94or%20hasn%E2%80%99t%E2%80%94changed.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EAlberuni%E2%80%99s%20Background%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAlberuni%20was%20one%20of%20the%20greatest%20scholars%20and%20scientists%20of%20the%20medieval%20age.%20Not%20much%20is%20known%20about%20his%20early%20life%2C%20but%20he%20was%20a%20product%20of%20what%E2%80%99s%20often%20called%20the%20%E2%80%98Golden%20Age%20of%20Islam%E2%80%99%E2%80%94a%20period%20of%20scientific%2C%20economic%2C%20and%20cultural%20flourishing%20during%20the%20Abbasid%20Caliphate%2C%20centred%20in%20Baghdad.%20Its%20creative%20spirit%20was%20more%20Persian%20than%20Arabic.%20Its%20elites%20were%20studying%20ancient%20Greek%20classics%2C%20mathematics%2C%20astronomy%2C%20optics%2C%20medicine%2C%20shipbuilding%2C%20poetry%2C%20literature%2C%20and%20philosophy.%20The%20folk%20tales%20of%20the%20Arabian%20Nights%20were%20compiled%20at%20this%20time.%20This%20was%20the%20age%20of%20luminaries%20like%20Avicenna%2C%20Al-Farabi%2C%20Omar%20Khayyam%2C%20Alhazen%2C%20and%20Firdausi.%20Some%20of%20these%20men%20were%20contemporaries%20of%20Alberuni.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAlberuni%20was%20likely%20born%20in%20the%20city%20of%20Khiva%20in%20Uzbekistan.%20Fluent%20in%20five%20languages%2C%20he%20was%20a%20gifted%20polymath.%20He%20excelled%20in%20mathematics%2C%20physics%2C%20geography%2C%20pharmacology%2C%20mineralogy%2C%20philosophy%2C%20history%2C%20and%20other%20disciplines.%20When%20he%20was%2060%2C%20he%20compiled%20a%20list%20of%20146%20books%20he%20had%20already%20written%2C%20only%2022%20of%20which%20have%20survived.%20In%20his%20writings%2C%20Alberuni%20rarely%20spoke%20about%20himself%2C%20but%20he%20comes%20across%20as%20a%20mildly%20devout%20Muslim%2C%20likely%20Shia%2C%20with%20some%20fondness%20for%20the%20Persian%20culture%20of%20Islam.%20He%20was%20tolerant%2C%20open-minded%2C%20and%20a%20big%20believer%20in%20science%2C%20reason%2C%20and%20evidence.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EThe%20Ghaznavids%20and%20Mahmud%20of%20Ghazni%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAt%20its%20peak%2C%20the%20Abassid%20Caliphate%20had%20highly%20disciplined%20armies%20whose%20eastern%20flanks%20were%20peopled%20by%20ethnic%20Turks%2C%20who%20had%20been%20converting%20to%20Islam%20from%20Buddhism%20and%20their%20native%20animistic%20faith%20called%20Tengrism.%20By%20the%20end%20of%20the%20millennium%2C%20some%20of%20the%20Caliphate%E2%80%99s%20Turkish%20generals%20had%20broken%20away%20and%20built%20independent%20kingdoms%2C%20retaining%20only%20a%20ceremonial%20attachment%20to%20the%20Caliph%20in%20Baghdad.%20One%20such%20kingdom%20in%20modern%20Afghanistan%20was%20led%20by%20the%20Ghaznavids%20(977-1186)%2C%20whose%20second%20king%20was%20the%20infamous%20Mahmud%20of%20Ghazni%20(971%E2%80%931030).%20He%20is%20quite%20justifiably%20viewed%20by%20many%20Indians%20as%20a%20fanatic%20warrior%2C%20a%20destroyer%20of%20temples%20and%20plunderer%20of%20their%20wealth.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EFrom%20the%20year%201001%2C%20Mahmud%20had%20started%20raiding%20India%E2%80%99s%20richest%20temples%20in%20places%20like%20Mathura%2C%20Thanesar%2C%20Kannauj%2C%20and%20Somnath.%20He%20raided%2017%20times%20over%20the%20next%2025%20years.%20Whether%20his%20primary%20motivation%20was%20material%20gain%20or%20religious%20fanaticism%20is%20now%20a%20contentious%20topic.%20What%20we%20do%20know%20is%20that%20Mahmud%20was%20bad%20news%20not%20just%20for%20Hindus%20in%20Indian%20temple%20towns.%20In%20other%20regions%2C%20he%20also%20plundered%20those%20he%20considered%20the%20%E2%80%98wrong%E2%80%99%20kinds%20of%20Muslims%2C%20such%20as%20Ismailis%20and%20Shias%2C%20and%20even%20desecrated%20their%20mosques.%20Mahmud%20also%20kept%20a%20division%20of%20loyal%20mercenary%20Hindus%20in%20his%20army%20who%20lived%20in%20a%20Hindu%20quarter%20in%20Ghazni%2C%20and%20one%20of%20whose%20commanders%20was%20named%20Tilak%E2%80%94a%20detail%20that%20ought%20to%20inform%20our%20assessments%20of%20Mahmud%20and%20his%20motivations.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EMahmud%E2%80%99s%20temple%20raids%20helped%20fund%20his%20Central%20Asian%20wars%20and%20turn%20Ghazni%20into%20a%20fine%20city%20with%20palaces%2C%20gardens%2C%20a%20huge%20library%2C%20a%20university%2C%20and%20a%20grand%20mosque.%20From%20his%20Central%20Asian%20raids%2C%20Mahmud%20brought%20to%20his%20court%20the%20greatest%20scholars%20and%20writers%20of%20the%20age.%20One%20of%20them%20was%20Alberuni%2C%20who%20Mahmud%20had%20brought%20as%20a%20prisoner%20of%20war%20from%20Khiva%20in%20Uzbekistan.%20Another%20captive%20was%20the%20great%20poet%20Firdausi%2C%20author%20of%20the%20Persian%20epic%2C%20Shahnameh%20(%E2%80%98The%20Book%20of%20Kings%E2%80%99).%20Firdausi%20managed%20to%20escape%20after%20some%20time%2C%20but%20this%20was%20how%20Mahmud%20tried%20to%20be%20a%20patron%20of%20the%20arts%20and%20science.%20And%20that%E2%80%99s%20largely%20how%20he%20is%20still%20remembered%20in%20Afghanistan.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3ECuriously%2C%20our%20knowledge%20of%20Mahmud%E2%80%99s%20raids%20is%20based%20entirely%20on%20Turko-Persian%20court%20chronicles.%20Hindu%20sources%20are%20silent%20about%20even%20the%20most%20infamous%20of%20his%20raids%E2%80%94on%20Somnath%20Temple%20in%201025.%20Nor%20do%20the%20Hindu%20sources%20suggest%20a%20sense%20of%20social%20trauma.%20Twelve%20years%20later%2C%20the%20account%20of%20a%20Goan%20king%E2%80%99s%20pilgrimage%20to%20Somnath%20temple%20mentioned%20neither%20any%20damage%2C%20nor%20the%20raid.%20In%20time%2C%20the%20local%20Gujarati%20and%20Turko-Persian%20merchants%20even%20began%20a%20thriving%20trade.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EScholars%20have%20puzzled%20over%20why%20Hindu%20chroniclers%20failed%20to%20record%20Mahmud%E2%80%99s%20attack%20on%20Somnath%20temple%2C%20and%20why%20his%20raid%20was%20apparently%20forgotten.%20One%20theory%20is%20that%20the%20damage%20wasn%E2%80%99t%20great%2C%20and%20the%20locals%20simply%20rebuilt%20and%20moved%20on%2C%20much%20as%20their%20ancestors%20had%20done%20when%20rival%20Indian%20kings%20raided%20and%20pillaged%20their%20temples.%20Somnath%20itself%20was%20a%20relatively%20new%20Shiva%20temple%20at%20the%20time%2C%20likely%20built%20over%20a%20Buddhist%20chaitya%E2%80%94a%20fate%20that%20many%20Buddhist%20sites%20suffered%20in%20the%20late%20first%20millennium.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EWhat%E2%80%99s%20really%20interesting%20is%20that%20it%20was%20only%20in%20the%2019th%20century%20that%20British%20scholars%20discovered%20Mahmud%E2%80%99s%20raids%20in%20dusty%20Turko-Persian%20archives.%20The%20British%20cited%20these%20raids%20to%20present%20their%20own%20colonial%20project%20as%20more%20%E2%80%98enlightened%E2%80%99%20and%20to%20divide%20and%20rule%20Indians.%20The%20Hindu%20revivalists%20of%20this%20period%20used%20this%20discovery%20for%20their%20own%20partisan%20ends%2C%20inventing%20the%20trope%20of%20the%20%E2%80%98thousand%20years%20of%20memory%E2%80%99%20and%20its%20lingering%20%E2%80%98social%20trauma%E2%80%99.%20This%20would%20soon%20become%20a%20foundational%20mythos%20of%20modern%20Hindu%20nationalism.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EAlberuni%E2%80%99s%20Approach%20to%20India%20%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAlberuni%20was%20a%20decent%20man.%20He%20hated%20Mahmud%2C%20and%2C%20after%20Mahmud%E2%80%99s%20death%20in%201030%20CE%2C%20denounced%20his%20raids%20on%20Hindu%20temples.%20In%20some%20of%20those%20raiding%20years%2C%20Alberuni%20had%20travelled%20in%20north%20India%20and%20noticed%20the%20damage%20caused%20by%20Mahmud.%20Led%20by%20his%20own%20curiosity%2C%20he%20spent%2013%20years%20studying%20Indian%20thought%20and%20society.%20He%20learned%20Sanskrit%20and%20studied%20the%20major%20works%20of%20Brahminism.%20He%20felt%20overwhelmed%20at%20first%20by%20the%20sheer%20volume%20of%20material%2C%20but%20he%20kept%20going.%20He%20sought%20out%20learned%20Brahmins%20to%20clarify%20his%20doubts.%20He%20even%20translated%20Sanskrit%20texts%20into%20Arabic%2C%20for%20instance%2C%20of%20Samkhya%20and%20Patanjali.%20In%201030%2C%20at%20age%2057%2C%20he%20published%20his%20magnum%20opus%20titled%2C%20%E2%80%99Verifying%20All%20That%20the%20Indians%20Recount%2C%20the%20Reasonable%20and%20the%20Unreasonable%E2%80%99.%20Its%2019th%20century%20English%20translation%20is%20simply%20called%20Alberuni%E2%80%99s%20India.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAlberuni%E2%80%99s%20native%20informants%20were%20Brahmins%2C%20since%20they%20dominated%20scholastic%20learning%20in%20India.%20He%20never%20came%20across%20Buddhism%2C%20because%2C%20as%20we%20saw%20earlier%20in%20this%20series%2C%20Buddhism%E2%80%99s%20demise%20from%20much%20of%20India%20predated%20Mahmud%20of%20Ghazni.%20So%20Alberuni%20mainly%20documented%20the%20customs%20and%20practices%20of%20Brahminical%20society.%20The%20focus%20of%20his%20book%2C%20as%20he%20says%20himself%2C%20%E2%80%98is%20that%20which%20the%20Brahmins%20think%20and%20believe.%E2%80%99%20He%20introduced%20their%20major%20religious%20texts%2C%20and%20highlighted%20parts%20of%20the%20Vedic%20corpus%2C%20the%20Bhagavad%20Gita%2C%20the%20Puranas%2C%20Patanjali%2C%20and%20stories%20from%20the%20two%20epics.%20He%20reviewed%20Indian%20scientific%20and%20astronomical%20texts.%20He%20compared%20Brahminical%20thought%20with%20the%20Greco-Roman%20thought%20of%20Socrates%2C%20Pythagoras%2C%20Plato%2C%20Aristotle%2C%20Galen%2C%20and%20also%20with%20Sufi%20thought.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EAlberuni%E2%80%99s%20Social%20Observations%20%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAlberuni%20admired%20many%20things%20in%20India%2C%20from%20its%20mathematics%20to%20the%20architecture%20of%20step%20wells.%20He%20describes%20how%20Indians%20made%20books%20from%20the%20bark%20of%20birch%20trees.%20Such%20a%20book%20was%20called%20puthi%2C%20from%20which%20we%20get%20pustaka.%20He%20saw%20a%20festival%20called%20Dibali%2C%20for%20which%20people%20dressed%20up%2C%20exchanged%20presents%2C%20visited%20temples%20and%20gave%20alms.%20At%20night%2C%20%E2%80%98they%20lit%20a%20great%20number%20of%20lamps%20in%20every%20place%E2%80%99.%20This%20celebration%20had%20nothing%20to%20do%20with%20Rama%20liberating%20Sita%2C%20but%20with%20a%20different%20story%20of%20Lakshmi%20liberating%20Bali%2C%20who%20was%20a%20prisoner%20in%20the%20seventh%20earth.%20The%20cult%20of%20Rama%20was%20apparently%20still%20small%2C%20and%20yet%20to%20be%20linked%20to%20the%20festival%20of%20lights%20in%20north%20India.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAlberuni%E2%80%99s%20social%20observations%20are%20perhaps%20the%20most%20interesting.%20Caste%20made%20a%20deep%20impression%20on%20him.%20It%20really%20bothered%20him%20that%20learned%20Hindus%20%E2%80%98did%20not%20mingle%20with%20foreigners%20%5Bmleccha%5D%20like%20him%2C%20as%20in%20sitting%2C%20eating%2C%20and%20drinking%20with%20them%2C%20for%20fear%20of%20being%20polluted%E2%80%99.%20Nor%20did%20they%20mingle%20with%20members%20of%20other%20varnas.%20Many%20outcaste%20groups%2C%20who%20performed%20essential%20services%2C%20were%20forced%20to%20live%20outside%20the%20walls%20of%20towns%20and%20villages.%20Alberuni%20despised%20social%20institutions%20that%2C%20he%20wrote%2C%20cannot%20%E2%80%98be%20broken%20through%20by%20the%20special%20merits%20of%20any%20individual%E2%80%99%2C%20and%20yet%20such%20institutions%20abound%20among%20the%20Hindus%2C%20he%20wrote.%20He%20called%20this%20the%20main%20difference%20between%20Hindus%20and%20his%20own%20people.%20%E2%80%98We%20Muslims%2C%E2%80%99%20he%20noted%20with%20some%20pride%2C%20%E2%80%98consider%20all%20men%20as%20equal%2C%20except%20in%20piety%E2%80%99.%20He%20seems%20to%20concede%20that%20Muslims%20can%20be%20more%20fanatical%20than%20Hindus%20about%20theological%20matters%2C%20but%20he%20thought%20that%20the%20Brahmins%20just%20expressed%20their%20fanaticism%20differently.%20It%20showed%20up%20in%20their%20obsessions%20with%20purity%20and%20their%20treatment%20of%20fellow%20humans%20as%20innately%20impure%20and%20inferior.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EA%20thousand%20years%20ago%2C%20Alberuni%20wrote%2C%20most%20%E2%80%98Brahmins%20recite%20the%20Veda%20without%20understanding%20its%20meaning%E2%80%99.%20They%20teach%20it%20to%20the%20Kshatriyas%2C%20but%20the%20Vaishyas%2C%20Shudras%20and%20the%20outcastes%20%E2%80%98are%20not%20allowed%20to%20hear%20it%2C%20much%20less%20to%20pronounce%20and%20recite%20it.%20If%20such%20a%20thing%20can%20be%20proved%20against%20one%20of%20them%2C%20the%20Brahmins%20drag%20him%20before%20the%20magistrate%2C%20and%20he%20is%20punished%20by%20having%20his%20tongue%20cut%20off%E2%80%99.%20This%20punishment%20was%20apparently%20rare%2C%20but%20the%20threat%20is%20indicative%20of%20the%20era%E2%80%99s%20social%20realities.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAccording%20to%20Alberuni%2C%20child%20marriages%20were%20the%20norm.%20A%20Hindu%20man%20could%20marry%20up%20to%20four%20women%2C%20depending%20on%20his%20place%20in%20the%20varna%20hierarchy.%20Brahmins%20were%20allowed%20four%20wives%2C%20Kshatriyas%20three%2C%20vaishyas%20two%2C%20and%20the%20Shudras%2C%20one.%20Alberuni%20wrote%20that%20a%20%E2%80%98husband%20and%20wife%20can%20only%20be%20separated%20by%20death%2C%20as%20the%20Hindus%20have%20no%20divorce.%E2%80%99%20If%20a%20wife%20died%2C%20the%20husband%20could%20marry%20another%20woman%2C%20but%20the%20reverse%20wasn%E2%80%99t%20allowed.%20A%20widow%20inherited%20nothing%20from%20her%20husband%E2%80%99s%20wealth%2C%20so%20her%20choices%20were%20to%3A%20(1)%20either%20remain%20a%20widow%20dependent%20on%20the%20kindness%20of%20her%20male%20relatives%3B%20or%20(2)%20burn%20herself%20on%20the%20husband%E2%80%99s%20funeral%20pyre%2C%20an%20event%20that%20was%20fortunately%20rare%20outside%20the%20Kshatriya%20class.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAlberuni%20described%20taxation%2C%20inheritance%2C%20cremation%20rites%2C%20crime%20and%20punishment.%20The%20common%20people%2C%20he%20wrote%2C%20lied%20about%20their%20property%20in%20order%20to%20lower%20their%20taxes%E2%80%94a%20custom%20we%E2%80%99ve%20tenaciously%20held%20on%20to!%20Female%20prostitution%20was%20legal%2C%20which%20included%20the%20temple%20devadasis.%20Alberuni%E2%80%99s%20morality%20and%20sexual%20conservatism%20did%20not%20approve%20of%20this%20practice.%20He%20faulted%20the%20kings%20for%20making%20prostitutes%20%E2%80%98an%20attraction%20for%20their%20cities%2C%20a%20bait%20of%20pleasure%20for%20their%20subjects%2C%20for%20only%20financial%20reasons%E2%80%99.%20It%20seems%20the%20taxes%20they%20paid%20offset%20the%20state%E2%80%99s%20military%20expenses.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EThe%20Brahmins%2C%20however%2C%20were%20exempt%20from%20all%20taxes.%20Even%20the%20law%20of%20the%20land%20treated%20them%20leniently.%20They%20literally%20got%20away%20with%20murder%2C%20asked%20only%20to%20atone%20for%20it%20by%20%E2%80%98fasting%2C%20prayers%2C%20and%20almsgiving%E2%80%99.%20Members%20of%20other%20castes%20faced%20harsher%20penalties%20for%20the%20same%20crime.%20Interestingly%2C%20the%20Brahmins%20were%20punished%20more%20for%20flouting%20the%20caste%20order.%20Alberuni%20wrote%2C%20%E2%80%98If%20a%20Brahman%20eats%20in%20the%20house%20of%20a%20Shudra%20for%20sundry%20days%2C%20he%20is%20expelled%20from%20his%20caste%20and%20can%20never%20regain%20it.%E2%80%99%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EAlberuni%20On%20Indian%20Science%20%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAlberuni%20was%20surprised%20by%20the%20mediocre%20state%20of%20Indian%20science.%20The%20%E2%80%98scientific%20theorems%20of%20the%20Hindus%E2%80%99%2C%20he%20wrote%2C%20%E2%80%98are%20in%20a%20state%20of%20utter%20confusion%E2%80%99%20and%20%E2%80%98mixed%20up%20with%20%E2%80%A6%20religious%20dogmas.%E2%80%99%20The%20Hindus%2C%20he%20added%2C%20do%20not%20%E2%80%98raise%20themselves%20to%20the%20methods%20of%20a%20strictly%20scientific%20deduction.%E2%80%99%20His%20views%20reflect%20the%20fact%20that%20a%20thousand%20years%20ago%2C%20science%20in%20the%20Persianate%20world%20was%20more%20advanced%20than%20in%20India%20and%20Europe.%20Indian%20astronomy%20had%20actually%20regressed%20in%20the%20500%20years%20since%20Aryabhata.%20Its%20leading%20astronomers%20now%20believed%20that%20the%20earth%20does%20not%20rotate%20on%20its%20axis%20but%20is%20at%20rest.%20So%20Alberuni%20showed%20them%20how%20to%20construct%20an%20astrolabe%20to%20understand%20the%20rotation%20of%20the%20earth.%20As%20we%20saw%20in%20a%20previous%20episode%2C%20Indian%20medicine%20too%20had%20long%20stagnated%2C%20partly%20because%20Brahminical%20healers%2C%20who%20monopolised%20formal%20education%2C%20avoided%20working%20with%20the%20%E2%80%98polluting%20fluids%E2%80%99%20of%20the%20body.%20Such%20%E2%80%98is%20the%20state%20of%20things%20in%20India%E2%80%99%2C%20Alberuni%20lamented%2C%20that%20Brahmins%20attempt%20to%20combine%20ideas%20of%20purity%20with%20the%20pursuit%20of%20science.%20No%20resemblance%20at%20all%20to%20our%20own%20age!%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EBut%20none%20of%20this%2C%20according%20to%20Alberuni%2C%20prevented%20the%20elites%20from%20having%20an%20inflated%20opinion%20of%20themselves.%20In%20a%20fit%20of%20annoyance%2C%20he%20wrote%3A%20The%20Hindus%20believe%20that%20no%20other%20people%20%E2%80%98besides%20them%20have%20any%20knowledge%20or%20science%20whatsoever.%20Their%20haughtiness%20is%20such%20that%2C%20if%20you%20tell%20them%20of%20any%20science%20or%20scholar%20in%20Khorasan%20and%20Persis%2C%20they%20will%20think%20you%20to%20be%20both%20an%20ignoramus%20and%20a%20liar.%20If%20they%20travelled%20and%20mixed%20with%20other%20nations%2C%20they%20would%20soon%20change%20their%20mind%2C%20for%20their%20ancestors%20were%20not%20as%20narrow-minded%20as%20the%20present%20generation%20is.%E2%80%99%20According%20to%20a%20modern%20scholar%20of%20this%20period%20%5BRichard%20Eaton%5D%2C%20%E2%80%98the%20smugly%20insular%20stance%20of%20Sanskrit%20scientific%20literature%20%E2%80%A6%20remained%20for%20centuries%20willfully%20ignorant%20of%20its%20competitors%E2%80%99.%20This%20situation%20improved%20somewhat%20after%20Persianate%20and%20Sanskritic%20cultures%20began%20mingling%20in%20India.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAlberuni%E2%80%99s%20account%20shows%20that%20on%20the%20eve%20of%20the%20Turko-Persian%20invasions%2C%20Brahminical%20society%20was%20not%20exactly%20a%20picture%20of%20intellectual%20and%20moral%20health%20that%20many%20now%20fondly%20imagine%20it%20to%20have%20been.%20Barring%20exceptions%20like%20Abhinavagupta%20of%20Kashmir%2C%20India%E2%80%99s%20urban%20intellectual%20culture%20seems%20to%20have%20declined%20in%20preceding%20centuries%3B%20it%20had%20fallen%20behind%20in%20science.%20Its%20Brahminical%20elites%20had%20grown%20insular%2C%20insecure%2C%20superstitious%2C%20caste-bound%2C%20lacking%20in%20creativity.%20By%20the%20late%20first%20millennium%2C%20growing%20Brahminical%20orthodoxy%20and%20Bhakti%20devotionalism%20had%20been%20crowding%20out%20the%20rational%20and%20liberal%20strains%20of%20Indian%20spirituality.%20Alberuni%E2%80%99s%20portrait%20of%20north%20India%20is%20so%20perceptive%20that%20he%20deserves%20to%20be%20called%20the%20%E2%80%98first%20Indologist%E2%80%99.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EMarco%20Polo%E2%80%99s%20Background%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EMarco%20Polo%20(1254%E2%80%931324)%20was%20a%20very%20different%20kind%20of%20man%20than%20Alberuni.%20A%20Venetian%20merchant%20and%20adventurer%2C%20Marco%20Polo%20had%20travelled%20the%20Silk%20Road%20from%20Europe%20to%20China.%20There%2C%20he%20ended%20up%20serving%20as%20the%20foreign%20emissary%20of%20the%20Mongol%20emperor%20Kublai%20Khan%20for%2017%20years%2C%20which%20took%20him%20all%20over%20Asia.%20He%20was%2038%20years%20old%20in%201292%2C%20when%20he%20stopped%20in%20south%20India%20on%20his%20way%20home%20from%20China.%20His%20ship%20landed%20near%20modern%20Thanjavur%20in%20Tamil%20Nadu%2C%20in%20the%20kingdom%20of%20the%20Pandyas.%20He%20spent%20a%20few%20months%20going%20around%20the%20Indian%20coast%2C%20finally%20sailing%20out%20of%20Gujarat.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3ELike%20Alberuni%2C%20Marco%20Polo%20was%20curious%2C%20open-minded%20and%20tolerant.%20He%20had%20a%20cosmopolitan%20spirit%20and%20a%20merchant%E2%80%99s%20pragmatic%20eye%2C%20but%20he%20had%20none%20of%20the%20scholarly%20temper%20of%20Alberuni.%20He%20was%20superstitious%2C%20gullible%2C%20and%20prone%20to%20exaggeration.%20He%20believed%20hearsay%20about%20giant%20birds%20that%20lifted%20elephants%2C%20men%20who%20looked%20like%20dogs%2C%20and%20other%20such%20fabulist%20tales.%20Fortunately%2C%20his%20account%20also%20contains%20fine%20social%20observations%2C%20and%20it%E2%80%99s%20usually%20not%20hard%20to%20separate%20the%20two.%20For%20instance%2C%20who%20would%20doubt%20his%20observation%20that%20Indians%20reserved%20their%20left%20hand%20for%20%E2%80%98unclean%20necessities%20like%20wiping%20the%20nostrils%2C%20anus%20and%20suchlike%E2%80%99.%20Or%20that%20Indians%20did%20not%20put%20their%20lips%20on%20flasks%2C%20preferring%20to%20%E2%80%98hold%20it%20above%20and%20pour%20the%20fluid%20into%20their%20mouths%E2%80%99.%20Or%20that%20Indians%20chewed%20a%20leaf%20called%20tambur%2C%20sometimes%20mixing%20it%20with%20camphor%2C%20spices%20and%20lime%2C%20and%20went%20about%20spitting%20it%20freely.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EMarco%20Polo%20On%20South%20Indians%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EThe%20hot%20climate%20of%20south%20India%20meant%20that%20all%20men%20and%20women%20wore%20nothing%20but%20a%20loincloth%2C%20including%20the%20kings%20and%20queens%E2%80%94except%20theirs%20were%20studded%20with%20rubies%2C%20sapphires%2C%20emeralds%20and%20other%20gems.%20Boys%20and%20girls%20went%20naked%20till%20seven%20years.%20Marco%20Polo%20called%20the%20Pandya%20kingdom%20%E2%80%98the%20richest%20and%20most%20splendid%20province%20in%20the%20world%E2%80%99%2C%20which%2C%20together%20with%20Ceylon%2C%20produced%20most%20of%20the%20pearls%20and%20gems%20of%20the%20world.%20The%20people%20consulted%20astrologers%2C%20he%20wrote%2C%20and%20had%20%E2%80%98enchanters%20called%20Brahmins%E2%80%99%2C%20who%20read%20mantras%20to%20protect%20the%20oyster%20divers%20against%20predatory%20fish.%20For%20this%20service%2C%20the%20brahmins%20received%20one%20in%20twenty%20pearls%20the%20divers%20extracted%20from%20the%20sea.%20Not%20a%20bad%20gig!%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EMarco%20Polo%20noticed%20the%20practice%20of%20sati%20among%20certain%20groups.%20People%20venerated%20the%20cow%20and%20daubed%20their%20houses%20with%20cow%20dung.%20They%20did%20not%20eat%20beef%E2%80%94except%20for%20a%20group%20with%20low%20social%20status%2C%20whose%20members%20were%20not%20admitted%20inside%20holy%20places%2C%20and%20who%20ate%20cattle%20that%20died%20a%20natural%20death.%20Marco%20Polo%20observed%20that%20people%20looked%20down%20on%20sailors%20and%20seafaring.%20This%20likely%20came%20from%20the%20Brahminical%20taboo%20of%20%3Cem%3Ekala%20pani%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20in%20which%20seafaring%20caused%20ritual%20pollution%20and%20loss%20of%20caste.%20Many%20Hindus%20still%20sailed%2C%20but%20this%20might%20help%20explain%20why%20the%20shipping%20lanes%20at%20the%20time%20were%20dominated%20not%20by%20Hindus%20but%20by%20Indian%20Muslims%2C%20Arabs%20and%20the%20Chinese.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EMarco%20Polo%20wrote%20about%20devadasis%20who%20sang%20and%20danced%20in%20temples%2C%20and%20traded%20sexual%20favours%20for%20money.%20It%20seemed%20to%20him%20that%20Indians%20did%20%E2%80%98not%20regard%20any%20form%20of%20sexual%20indulgence%20as%20a%20sin%E2%80%99%2C%20a%20remark%20best%20understood%20in%20light%20of%20his%20strong%20Christian%20morality.%20Marco%20Polo%20also%20wrote%20that%20dark%20skin%20was%20preferred%20by%20Indians.%20When%20a%20child%20is%20born%2C%20he%20wrote%2C%20they%20rub%20an%20oil%20on%20her%20skin%20to%20make%20her%20grow%20darker%2C%20because%20darker%20people%20were%20more%20highly%20esteemed%20than%20the%20lighter-skinned%20ones.%20That%E2%80%99s%20why%20their%20gods%20were%20all%20black%20%E2%80%98and%20their%20devils%20white%20as%20snow%E2%80%99.%20It%E2%80%99s%20possible%20that%20the%20higher%20value%20for%20lighter%20skin%20that%20had%20emerged%20with%20the%20spread%20of%20Indo-Aryan%20culture%2C%20hadn%E2%80%99t%20yet%20penetrated%20folk%20culture%20this%20far%20south.%20Cultural%20standards%20of%20beauty%20have%20of%20course%20changed%20dramatically%20since%20then.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EMarco%20Polo%E2%80%99s%20Spicy%20Tales%20%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EMarco%20Polo%E2%80%99s%20account%20is%20also%20full%20of%20spicy%2C%20gossipy%20tales.%20Like%20the%20story%20of%20a%20king%20who%20kept%20500%20wives%20and%20concubines.%20%E2%80%98Whenever%20he%20set%20eyes%20on%20a%20beautiful%20woman%20or%20damsel%2C%20he%20took%20her%20for%20himself%E2%80%99.%20Yet%20he%20coveted%20the%20wife%20of%20his%20brother%20who%20was%20also%20a%20king%20of%20a%20nearby%20region.%20He%20even%20managed%20to%20%E2%80%98steal%E2%80%99%20her%20away.%20A%20war%20between%20the%20brothers%20was%20prevented%20only%20by%20their%20mother%E2%80%99s%20emotional%20blackmail%2C%20when%20she%20threatened%20to%20cut%20off%20her%20breasts%20with%20a%20knife.%20This%20is%20the%20story%20he%20tells%3B%20we%20have%20no%20way%20of%20verifying%20if%20it%E2%80%99s%20true.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EIn%20another%20story%2C%20Marco%20Polo%20met%20holy%20men%20who%20went%20stark%20naked%20and%20led%20austere%20lives.%20They%20believed%20that%20all%20creatures%20had%20a%20soul%20and%20took%20pains%20to%20avoid%20hurting%20even%20the%20tiniest%20of%20them.%20When%20asked%20why%20they%20did%20not%20cover%20their%20private%20parts%2C%20they%20said%2C%20%E2%80%98We%20go%20naked%20because%20we%20want%20nothing%20of%20this%20world.%20For%20we%20came%20into%20this%20world%20naked%20and%20unclothed%20.%20.%20.%20It%E2%80%99s%20because%20you%20employ%20this%20member%20in%20sin%20and%20lechery%20that%20you%20cover%20it%20and%20are%20ashamed%20of%20it.%20But%20we%20are%20no%20more%20ashamed%20of%20it%20than%20of%20our%20fingers.%E2%80%99%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EAnother%20vignette%20comes%20from%20the%20Thanjavur%20region%20of%20Tamil%20Nadu%2C%20where%2C%20according%20to%20custom%2C%20%E2%80%98the%20king%20and%20his%20barons%20and%20everyone%20else%20all%20sit%20on%20the%20earth%E2%80%99.%20He%20asked%20them%20why%20they%20%E2%80%98do%20not%20seat%20themselves%20more%20honourably%E2%80%99.%20The%20king%20replied%2C%20%E2%80%98To%20sit%20on%20the%20earth%20is%20honourable%20enough%2C%20because%20we%20were%20made%20from%20the%20earth%20and%20to%20the%20earth%20we%20must%20return.%E2%80%99%20I%20think%20we%20could%20certainly%20use%20a%20few%20similarly%20grounded%20politicians%20today!%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EMarco%20Polo%20also%20visited%20the%20tomb%20of%20St%20Thomas%20the%20Apostle%20near%20Chennai%2C%20a%20place%20of%20pilgrimage%20for%20local%20Christians%20and%20Muslims.%20He%20wrote%20that%20Indians%20imported%20over%202000%20horses%20from%20Aden%20every%20year.%20But%20most%20of%20them%20died%20because%20Indians%20didn%E2%80%99t%20know%20how%20to%20care%20for%20them.%20He%20mentioned%20a%20kingdom%20%E2%80%98ruled%20by%20a%20queen%2C%20a%20very%20wise%20woman.%E2%80%99%20Historians%20think%20this%20was%20Rudrama%20Devi%20of%20the%20Kakatiya%20Dynasty%20of%20Warangal.%20He%20praised%20the%20fine%20cotton%20textiles%20of%20south%20India.%20He%20admired%20wine%20made%20out%20of%20dates%20in%20Kerala.%20He%20noticed%20leather%20workshops%2C%20pepper%20and%20indigo%20plantations%2C%20and%20was%20visibly%20thrilled%20by%20the%20beautiful%20birds%20and%20animals%20of%20south%20India.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EOther%20Travellers%E2%80%99%20Accounts%20%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EOther%20travellers%20after%20Marco%20Polo%20have%20given%20us%20additional%20insights%20into%20south%20India.%20These%20include%20Ibn%20Battuta%2C%20who%20visited%20in%20the%201340s.%20He%20described%20huge%20Chinese%20ships%20in%20the%20Calicut%20harbour%2C%20some%20with%20four%20decks%2C%20cabins%20with%20toilets%2C%20and%20a%20thousand%20people%20on%20board!%20Battuta%20called%20the%20Chinese%20the%20wealthiest%20people%20in%20the%20world%2C%20who%20dominated%20the%20shipping%20industry%20around%20the%2013th%20to%2015th%20centuries.%20Calicut%20had%20a%20large%20resident%20community%20of%20Malayali-speaking%20Muslims%20called%20Mappilas%2C%20dating%20from%20at%20least%20the%20ninth%20century.%20They%20and%20others%20in%20the%20region%20had%20matrilineal%20societies.%20Some%20groups%20even%20practised%20polyandry.%20Clearly%2C%20Indian%20social%20norms%20were%20a%20lot%20more%20diverse%20in%20Battuta%E2%80%99s%20time%20than%20our%20narrowly%20patriarchal%20norms%20today.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EIn%20the%2013th%20century%2C%20parts%20of%20south%20India%20saw%20much%20political%20churn%20and%20military%20violence.%20Some%20of%20it%20was%20driven%20by%20the%20expansionary%20Delhi%20Sultanate%E2%80%94whose%20Turko-Afghan%20warriors%20possessed%20a%20culture%20of%20greater%20military%20discipline%2C%20battlefield%20innovations%2C%20and%20meritocracy.%20When%20the%20dust%20settled%20in%20the%20early%201300s%2C%20the%20Delhi%20Sultanate%20ruled%20in%20the%20north%2C%20and%20two%20new%20entities%20had%20appeared%20in%20south%20India%3A%20The%20Bahmani%20Sultanate%20and%20the%20Vijayanagar%20Empire.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%3EIn%20the%20next%20episode%2C%20I%E2%80%99ll%20look%20at%20the%20rise%20and%20fall%20of%20the%20Vijayanagar%20Empire%2C%20and%20the%20secrets%20of%20its%20wealth%2C%20military%20power%2C%20and%20cosmopolitan%20culture%20that%20many%20foreign%20travellers%20wrote%20about.%20See%20you%20next%20time!%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1708769511000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F24154024%2Fimage-1872.png%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fhistory%2Fwatch-indians-episode-7-alberuni-and-marco-polo-in-india%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Led%20by%20his%20own%20curiosity%2C%20Alberuni%20spent%201